Part 3

The casualty door opened again, letting in the cool night breeze and the distant rumble of the city roads. This time, a different doctor entered, younger than the others on duty. 

His white coat still looked new, the stiff crease of the laundry iron visible along the sleeves. His stethoscope was carefully placed around his neck, not hanging carelessly like the experienced doctors did. 

He walked toward the nurses' station, his shoes clicking softly on the grey floor tiles. He stopped, looking at the unusual crowd that had gathered near the ICU doors.

"What happened?" he asked the receptionist.

The receptionist looked up from her ledger, her glasses sliding down her nose. "Road accident case, sir."

"Anyone serious?"

"An old man. Hit and run near the bypass."

"Name?"

The receptionist checked the register, her finger tracing the fresh ink on the page. "Vikram Ahuja."

The doctor's hand stopped midway while signing the attendance sheet. He looked up slowly, his face going pale. "What?"

"Vikram Ahuja," she said again.

"Age?"

"Around fifty," the receptionist said, checking the entry.

The doctor stood completely still, the pen still held between his fingers. The receptionist noticed his silence. "Sir... you know him?"

Adarsh didn't answer. He simply turned and walked toward the ICU doors, his steps slow and heavy, as if he were trying to remember something, or perhaps trying to forget.

---

Inside the ICU, the old man remained unconscious. The monitors beeped in a dry, regular rhythm, and the saline drips ran quietly into his arm. An oxygen mask covered half his face. 

Adarsh stood outside the glass door, staring at the patient. One minute passed, then another, the green lights of the monitors reflecting off his glasses.

The senior nurse came and stood beside him. "Dr. Tripathy... the patient is stable now."

He didn't respond immediately. He looked at the bandaged forehead, the dried blood near the ear, the white beard, and the wrinkled skin.

She studied his face. "You know him?"

He finally spoke, his voice very soft. "I don't know."

"What?"

"I knew someone..." He stopped. "A long time ago."

"Same name?"

"Yes."

"Same person?"

Adarsh looked at the unconscious face, at the old cotton shirt, and at the rubber slippers kept under the stretcher. "I don't know."

The nurse smiled slightly, trying to ease the tension. "Sir... you're a doctor. Check the file."

She handed him the case sheet. He opened it. 

Date of birth: *07-07-1977.* He calculated quickly. Around fifty. It matched. 

Father's name: *Binay Ahuja.* His hand trembled slightly as he read the name. 

Address: *Unknown.* Occupation: *Unknown.* Relationship with attendant: *NGO Volunteer.*

He closed the file. He looked again at the old man, then quietly walked away toward the canteen. 

The nurse called behind him. "Sir... you know him or not?"

He stopped near the exit, turning back. "I knew someone named Vikram Ahuja," he said. "But that Vikram would never become Budha Baba."

---

Dr. Adarsh Tripathy walked toward the canteen. He didn't want tea; he simply needed time to think. 

The hospital canteen was always the same. Old plastic chairs, stained tables, a ceiling fan rotating slowly, and tea that tasted exactly like yesterday's tea. 

He sat in the corner, ordering nothing, and stared at the wall. 

*Vikram Ahuja. Binay Ahuja. Date of birth 07-07-1977.* 

Everything matched, yet everything felt wrong. That Vikram wore branded clothes; this Budha Baba wore torn cotton. That Vikram was always surrounded by friends; this old man was brought by an NGO volunteer. That Vikram talked about building companies; this man apparently told crow stories to school children.

The tea seller came to his table anyway, setting down a glass. "Sir... regular?"

Adarsh nodded without looking. The tea arrived. He held the glass, felt the warmth, and remembered.

---

Twenty-eight years ago. 1995. The year everything began.

He was eighteen then, a first-year MBBS student. 

The dissection hall had smelled of formaldehyde, steel trays, and wet lime. A chart of the human skeleton hung on the wall. 

There were forty students, ten dissection tables, and complete chaos. 

"Where is my scalpel?" 

"Who took the forceps?" 

"Sir... the specimen is missing a label." 

"Careful... careful..." 

Someone knocked over a glass jar. There was a burst of laughter, then a professor's scolding, and then the normal noise returned.

Adarsh stood near table seven, alone. His partner hadn't arrived yet. The lab assistant was distributing white aprons, shouting at the class.

"Wear them properly! This is not chemistry. Respect the body. Breakage of instruments will be charged."

Nobody listened completely. Everyone wore their aprons carelessly. Except one boy. 

He wore it carefully, tying the strings properly and checking the pockets. Then he quietly walked toward table seven. He looked at Adarsh. "Partner?"

Adarsh nodded.

The boy smiled slightly, extending his hand. "Vicky."

Adarsh shook his hand. "Adarsh."

"Tripathy?" the boy asked.

Adarsh was surprised. "How do you know?"

Vicky pointed at the apron. On the left pocket, someone had stitched a name using blue thread: *Adarsh Tripathy.* 

Small letters, neat stitching. It was his mother's handiwork. Adarsh felt a little embarrassed. "My mother..."

Vicky's smile changed. "My mom would have done the same," he said. He paused, his eyes looking at the wall. "But she is no more with me. Lost her when I was young. Never seen her."

Adarsh didn't know what to say. "Sorry" felt too small for the dissection hall.

Vicky's eyes went somewhere else, almost wet. Then he blinked, came back, and picked up the scalpel. He checked its edge against the light, his face going calm. Just like that, the emotion appeared and disappeared.

Adarsh said nothing. They began the dissection—cutting, observing, and labeling.

---

"Pass the forceps," Vicky said.

"Done?"

"Wait."

Midway through the practical, the lab assistant shouted, "Five minutes remaining!" 

Everyone hurried. Mistakes and confusion increased, but Vicky remained calm. He completed every step properly, without any hurry. 

Adarsh noticed. This boy was different. He wasn't showing off; he was simply focused.

Professor Khanna walked between the tables. He had a white beard and a reputation for failing half the class. He stopped at table seven. 

He read the stitched name aloud. "Adarsh Tripathy."

Adarsh froze, his scalpel suspended.

"Your mother did this?" the professor asked.

"Yes, sir."

A pause. Then the professor smiled. "Good. At least someone's mother believes her son will pass my class."

There was scattered laughter in the hall. The professor moved on.

Vicky whispered, "Saved you."

"Saved me? He announced my name to the whole hall," Adarsh said.

"Better than him announcing you can't hold a scalpel properly," Vicky replied. 

It was a fair point.

---

The bell rang once more just as someone in row three knocked a glass specimen jar off the edge of table four. It didn't break; it simply rolled under the bench with a hollow, rubber-sealed sound and stopped. Everyone looked at it. Nobody moved immediately.

Then someone said, "Who dropped their ring?"

It was Mehta, a boy from table two, patting his pockets in sudden panic. He looked at the bench. He looked at the row of glass waste containers along the wall, the tall ones filled with formaldehyde solution and discarded tissue fragments from two weeks of dissections. 

"It slipped off my finger," he said, very quietly.

The ring was visible, if you looked carefully through the thick greenish liquid of the nearest barrel—a thin silver band, resting on the settled layer of pale organic waste at the bottom.

Mehta looked at the barrel. He looked at his hand. He made no move toward it.

"Nobody is putting their hand in that," the boy at table five said, very matter-of-factly. "It is not worth a tetanus shot."

Several heads nodded.

"I'll give you a hundred rupees if you pull it out," somebody offered from the back, with the casual confidence of a person who was quite sure nobody would take the offer.

Vikram set down his forceps, walked to the barrel, pushed his right sleeve up to the elbow, and put his arm in without any particular ceremony. His face didn't change.

The liquid was cold. That was the first thing. The second thing, which nobody in the room had anticipated, was the complete silence that fell over forty students the moment his arm went in past the wrist.

He found the ring by touch, lifted it out, and placed it on the edge of the barrel. Then he walked to the sink, turned the tap on, and washed his arm thoroughly with the carbolic soap kept there, scrubbing between the fingers twice.

Mehta took his ring, said thank you, and cleaned it with the hem of his lab coat.

Vikram dried his hands and went back to table seven.

"You didn't even hesitate," Adarsh said.

"I did," Vikram said, picking up the forceps again. "Just not long enough for anyone to notice."

---

The bell rang. "Submit your observations."

Everyone rushed toward the professor's desk. Vicky and Adarsh submitted their papers together. Khanna checked them, nodded, and said, "Good."

They removed their aprons, kept them on the rack, and walked out.

Outside the hall, someone called. "Aye... first year."

Four seniors stood near the staircase. Second-year students. It was the ragging season. 

Adarsh felt nervous, his throat going dry. Vicky remained calm beside him. The seniors walked closer.

"Name?"

Adarsh answered immediately. "Adarsh Tripathy."

One senior laughed. "Tripathy... Brahmin?"

"Yes."

"Bad luck. General category. No quota, no backup. Pure merit for you, poor fellow."

Everyone laughed. Adarsh said nothing, looking at the steps. Then they turned to Vicky.

"You?"

"Vicky."

The senior blinked. "Vicky?" He turned to the others. "Vicky? That's a dog's name, yaar. My cousin's Pomeranian is called Vicky."

Everyone laughed harder. Vikram's face didn't change.

"Full name," the senior demanded.

A pause. Then Vikram answered. "Vikram Ahuja."

The laughter stopped. "Ahuja... business family?"

Vikram didn't answer.

The senior pressed. "Rich family?"

"I don't know," Vikram said.

"You don't know if your family is rich?" There was laughter again.

Another senior interrupted. "Arre, leave him. Look at his shoes. Nike. Definitely rich."

Vikram looked at his shoes. Then he looked at Adarsh's cheap rubber slippers. He felt uncomfortable—not because of the seniors, but because of the comparison.

One senior stepped closer. "First year riddle. Answer fast."

Vikram waited.

"Which part of the body has no bone, is full of flesh, but is the most sensitive? Nerve endings everywhere."

Silence. Vikram's ears went red. He looked at the ground, refusing to answer. 

Adarsh understood the trap. He tried to help, pulling his own tongue out, wiggling it, and pointing at it.

The seniors burst out laughing. "Oye! Pervert! It's the tongue, man! What were *you* thinking?"

Vikram's face went from red to redder. "I... I knew that," he said.

"Sure you did," the senior laughed. "Next one. Which part, if you put a finger inside, water comes out?"

Vikram, still flustered, blurted the first thing. "Eye."

The seniors erupted. "Eye? Bro! Should I put my finger in your eye and check? Let's see how much water comes out."

There was laughter loud enough for two floors below. Even Adarsh laughed this time. Vikram's ears stayed red, but then he laughed too—small, reluctant, but real.

The senior turned to Adarsh. "You. Sing a song."

Adarsh's throat closed. He sang two lines, badly.

"Enough. Terrible voice. Go."

They didn't dismiss Vikram. "You. Stay."

Vikram glanced at Adarsh, giving a small shake of the head. *Go.*

Adarsh walked a few steps, slowed down, and listened.

"Rich boy," the senior was saying. "You think your papa's money matters here?"

"No," Vikram said.

"Good. Remember that."

Adarsh heard footsteps. Vikram caught up with him near the gate. Neither spoke for a while.

Then Adarsh asked, "Your name... Bikram or Vikram?"

"Vikram."

"Why did you say Vicky?"

Vikram smiled, his smile small and tired. "Everyone calls me Vicky. It's easier."

They reached the canteen, ordered tea, and sat on the wooden bench outside. The afternoon sun filtered through the trees, casting shadows on the ground. 




---

The chicken liberation happened four days later. This fact still embarrasses me to recall, but it belongs in the story.

It was Vicky's idea, which means it was the kind of idea that sounds obviously correct at eleven o'clock at night in a hostel room when two people have been studying for six hours on an empty stomach.

The college canteen, which closed at nine, kept five chickens in a wire coop behind the kitchen. They were not pets. Everyone knew what they were for. On Friday nights, the canteen served a chicken curry that was thinned with water and thickened with prayer, which is perhaps why it always tasted exactly the same.

"It is wrong," Vikram said. He was lying on his bed with the Pathology textbook balanced on his chest, looking at the ceiling. He had stopped reading half an hour ago. "They are just sitting there, knowing. Every day they know."

"They are chickens, Vicky."

"They still know," he said, with complete seriousness.

Adarsh put his pen down. He looked at Vikram. Then, unfortunately, he looked at the window. Then at the canteen building, visible from their room as a low, dark shape across the cricket ground.

"We would be expelled," Adarsh said.

"Probably," Vikram agreed.

There was a silence.

"The gate at the back of the canteen doesn't have a lock," Vikram said. "The latch lifts from outside."

Adarsh closed his Pharmacology notes.

---

They lifted the latch at half past eleven. The five chickens, startled awake, immediately made the kind of sound that five alarmed chickens make at midnight, which is to say, an extremely large sound for a small creature. Adarsh spent most of the operation frozen near the wall, certain that the warden's light would switch on at any moment.

Vikram guided all five through the gate with the calm determination of a man carrying out something he had already made his peace with. The chickens ran. They ran in five different directions, which was probably four more directions than either of them had planned for.

They walked back to the hostel.

In the morning, Adarsh looked across the cricket ground toward the canteen. The canteen cook was at the back gate, looking at the empty wire coop with his arms folded. He looked neither surprised nor particularly upset. He looked like a man who had expected something like this to happen eventually.

By afternoon, two of the chickens had been found crossing the main road and returned to the coop by the gate security guard, who was given five rupees for the trouble. 

One was found in the garden of the Registrar's office, pecking serenely at the marigold beds. The Registrar, a thin man who took the college compound very seriously, had it removed with considerable ceremony and some shouting.

One was sold that same evening by a man from the neighboring village who had found it near the bypass, to a small dhaba on the highway, for eleven rupees.

The fifth was killed by a stray dog near the college wall before noon.

Vikram heard all of this in pieces over the course of the day. He didn't say anything for most of it. At dinner, staring at the same chicken curry that had appeared on schedule regardless of the morning's events, he simply picked up his spoon.

"We made it worse," Adarsh said.

"Yes," Vikram said. He ate the curry. So did Adarsh.

There are some lessons that only register after the fact. Sometimes not even then.

---

The following weekend, Adarsh went home. His mother had saved enough from the grocery money for his bus fare, and the house smelled of mustard oil and the blue soap she kept wrapped in a cloth at the bottom of the tin trunk, the one she used only on his clothes.

His father, Pandit Tripathy, was a government clerk who had worked in the same municipal records office for twenty-two years. He had the habit of reading the newspaper from the last page forward, because the front page, he said, was always someone else's disaster, while the back page at least had the cricket scores.

He sat across from Adarsh after dinner, his reading glasses pushed to the top of his head. He had that look, the one Adarsh recognized from all the serious conversations of his childhood—forward in the chair, elbows on knees, the way a man sits when he has been waiting for a moment to say something.

"This friend of yours," his father said. "The one you wrote to your mother about. Ahuja."

"Vikram," Adarsh said.

"Ahuja," his father repeated, as though the surname was the point. "Binay Ahuja's son. From Odisha."

"I don't know his father's name."

"I know his father's name," his father said, with the exact tone of a man who has done a small, careful amount of research and is not embarrassed about it. "He is not a small man."

"Vikram's not like that, Baba," Adarsh said. "He wore rubber slippers on the first day. He tied his apron strings properly. He's—"

"I am not saying he is a bad boy," his father said, interrupting gently but firmly. "I am saying be careful. Rich men's sons are easy to like. That is part of the problem."

Adarsh waited.

"They are generous," his father continued, looking down at his folded hands. "They share food, they pay the rickshaw, they don't count the money. And slowly, without anyone meaning for it to happen, you start to feel less, Adarsh. Not because they try to make you feel less. Simply because the comparison is always there. Quietly. Like a piece of furniture you step around every day without noticing anymore."

"He's not like that."

"You said that already." His father looked at him directly. "I believe you. I'm asking you to watch, anyway. That's all. Watch, and keep your own ground."

Adarsh went back to college two days later. He told Vikram nothing of the conversation. 

But he found himself noticing, for the rest of that semester, whether the comparison was ever quietly there.

It wasn't. Or perhaps it was, and Vikram was simply the kind of person who made it invisible. He never paid for the rickshaw without asking first. He never spent in a way that created a gap. When Adarsh's rubber slippers finally split open along the sole in February, Vikram said nothing about it, which was the correct response. His father would not have believed this, but it was true.

Pandit Tripathy's warning was one of those. Adarsh only understood this many years later, sitting in a hospital canteen with a cold glass of tea, thinking about a man he was not sure he recognized anymore.

---

Dr. Adarsh Tripathy opened his eyes. The hospital canteen returned, the ceiling fan still clicking. 

His tea had become cold, and he hadn't taken a single sip.

The tea seller asked, "Sir... shall I change it?"

Adarsh looked at the glass, shook his head, and said, "No."

He stood up and walked back toward the casualty ward. The crowd near the ICU had grown even larger. Someone had brought flowers, and someone else had brought a small basket of fruits. A small child held a hand-drawn greeting card.

The NGO girl still sat on the same chair, holding the walking stick, waiting.

Adarsh stood at a distance, watching everything. Then he slowly walked toward the ICU door.

The nurse saw him. "Sir... did you remember?"

He nodded. "College friend."

"You are sure?"

"Same name. Same father's name. Same date of birth."

"Then why did you say you don't know?"

Adarsh looked through the glass at the unconscious man. "Because..." He stopped. How could he explain? The Vikram he knew was supposed to become something else. Not this.

The nurse waited for the answer. Adarsh simply said, "Because I don't know what happened between then and now."

He walked away, but his mind remained inside the ICU.

---

That evening, Budha Baba's condition improved. The blood transfusion was completed, the bleeding stopped, and his vitals became stable. 

The senior doctor allowed one visitor. The NGO girl immediately stood up and entered the ICU. 

She stood beside the bed, looking at the old man. His eyes remained closed, but his breathing had become normal. She didn't say anything; she simply kept her hand on his, very softly, as though reassuring herself he was still alive. 

After two minutes, she quietly left.

Outside, the entire crowd looked at her, waiting for news. She smiled. "He is better."

There was a wave of relief. Immediately, the little boy shouted, "Baba will tell the crow story now!"

Everyone smiled, even the serious-looking security guard.

The NGO girl sat back on her chair. This time, she finally noticed her own injury. Blood had dried on her elbow, her sleeve was torn, and she hadn't even cleaned it.

A nurse came with cotton and Dettol. "Let me see."

The girl hesitated.

The nurse understood. "I know. AIDS. I'll be careful." She cleaned the wound and applied a bandage. "You should have treated this first."

The girl smiled. "Baba was more important."

"Why?"

The girl looked toward the ICU. "Because... he taught me that life is bigger than diseases."

The nurse didn't understand completely, but she didn't ask further.

---

Dr. Adarsh Tripathy completed his duty at 8 PM. He signed the register and removed his white coat, but he didn't leave immediately. He walked back toward the ICU one more time.

The crowd had reduced slightly, but the NGO girl still remained. He stood beside her.

She looked up. "Doctor sahib... he will recover, right?"

Adarsh nodded. "He will."

"When can we take him home?"

"A few days."

She nodded, relieved.

Adarsh hesitated, then asked, "You know him since long?"

"Three years."

"How did you meet him?"

She smiled. "He came to our NGO. Said he wanted to teach children. No salary. Just time pass."

Adarsh felt strange hearing this. Vikram Ahuja, the son of Binay Ahuja, teaching children for "time pass." Something didn't fit.

"What does he teach?"

"Everything. Maths. Science. Stories. Life."

"Where does he live?"

"Near the NGO. A small room."

"Alone?"

"Yes."

"No family?"

The girl thought for a moment. "Baba never talks about family."

Adarsh wanted to ask more, but he stopped. Instead, he asked something else. "What is your name?"

"Ananya."

"You work in the NGO?"

"Yes. HIV awareness program."

Adarsh understood why she had the virus—it was probably contracted during her own struggle before she found the shelter. "Thank you for bringing him here."

Ananya smiled. "I should thank him. He brought me here three years ago. Same hospital. Different reason."

Adarsh waited.

"When I got my HIV report," she said, her voice dropping. "I tried to end my life. Pills. Hospital. Stomach wash. Baba was the only one who visited me. Every single day. Until I walked out alive."

She looked at Adarsh. "Today... I returned the favor."

Adarsh said nothing. He simply nodded, his hand going to his jacket pocket, his fingers finding his keys for no particular reason, not knowing what else to do with them. Then he quietly left.

---

Outside the hospital, the night had become completely dark. Auto rickshaws honked, street vendors shouted, and normal city life went on.

Adarsh stood near the gate, trying to process everything. 

*Vikram Ahuja. Budha Baba. Same person. Different life. What happened?*

He knew only one thing clearly: tomorrow, when Vikram woke up, he would ask—not as a doctor, but as an old friend.

Back in the ICU, around 11 PM, the monitor beeped differently. The duty nurse checked his vitals and smiled. The patient was waking up. 

She informed the senior doctor, who came immediately. "Good. Consciousness returning. Keep monitoring."

Around 11:30 PM, the old man's eyes slowly opened. First confused, then focused. He saw the white ceiling, smelled the hospital air, and heard the beeping machines.

He tried to remember. The road. The auto. The sudden crash. The children screaming. Ananya's voice. Then darkness.

He tried to speak, but his throat was dry.

The nurse came closer. "Baba... you are in the hospital. Don't worry. You are safe now."

He blinked, trying to understand, and drank a few drops of water she offered.

"Ananya?" he whispered.

"Outside. Waiting."

He tried to sit up, but the nurse held his shoulder gently. "Careful, Baba."

He lay back, closing his eyes again, but this time he was just tired, very tired.

The nurse stepped out and told Ananya, "He woke up. Asked for you."

Ananya smiled, tears coming suddenly. She didn't enter the ICU; she simply folded her hands toward the door, whispering, "Thank you."

---

That night, Dr. Adarsh couldn't sleep. He kept thinking of the pathology textbook, the blue name stitched on the white apron, and their first meeting.

*What happened after college? Where did he go? Why didn't they stay in touch? How did Vikram become Budha Baba?*

Questions without answers. He knew tomorrow he would get some answers, but he also knew some questions would remain forever.

[End of Part 3]